# Process Kill Guard

**Never run process-termination commands without explicit user confirmation in that same turn.**

Covered commands (non-exhaustive):
- `pkill`, `killall`
- `kill -9`, `kill -SIGKILL`, `kill -SIGTERM` targeting PIDs not started in the current command chain
- `fuser -k`, `lsof`-based kill pipelines

## Rule

Before executing any of the above, pause and ask:

> "This will terminate [process/pattern]. Confirm?"

Wait for an affirmative reply. Do not proceed on inference, ambiguity, or assumed intent.

## Rationale

The user may have multiple long-running sessions active across contexts (paude, editors, dev servers, etc.). A broad `pkill` targeting a pattern like `pi`, `node`, or `python` can wipe all of them silently. The cost of killing the wrong thing is high; the cost of asking is one round-trip.

## Exception

Commands that kill a process the agent **explicitly started in the same turn** (e.g. a test server spawned two steps earlier in the same task) do not require confirmation — the scope is known and bounded.
